# ethers v6 + Hardhat ENS Resolution Fix
When passing address arguments to contract calls (grantRole, setIndependentAggregator,
registerFarmer, mintBatch, etc.), ALWAYS wrap with ethers.getAddress():
  await contract.grantRole(ROLE, ethers.getAddress(signer.address));
This prevents HardhatEthersProvider.resolveName errors.
Exception: deployProxy arguments (e.g., [admin.address]) do NOT need wrapping.
Exception: hasRole() assertions (e.g., hasRole(ROLE, admin.address)) do NOT need wrapping.

# SENTINEL GUARD PATTERN
When a mapping value of 0 can be both "uninitialized/default" and a
valid state (e.g. score=0, loanAmount=0), always use a separate
mapping(address => bool) to track explicit initialization. The getter
must check the bool, not compare the value to 0. This avoids the
ambiguous-zero bug. A common pattern:
  mapping(address => uint256) public values;
  mapping(address => bool) public initialized;
  function getValue(address a) public view returns (uint256) {
      return initialized[a] ? values[a] : DEFAULT_VALUE;
  }
Flag this when designing LendingVault and any contract where
a state variable can legitimately equal zero.

# IBatchToken INTERFACE RULE
Keep IBatchToken.sol minimal — only export what LendingVault consumes:
checkExists, hasActiveLoan, lockAsCollateral, unlockCollateral, burnSettled.
Do NOT add struct-based batch data getters (causes ABI mismatch).

